postcontent: Nice example of a very early Norinco SKS.  This was produced in the days when Norincos were literally made on Russian machinery with true Russian blueprints.  This gun is ALL MILLED, with a screwed in barrel and blade bayonet.  NO cheap stampings or pinned barrels here. Chambered in 7.62x39.  Stock is covered in small battle scars and dings and is no beauty queen but I would say the metal is in approximately 85% condition. A very nice condition Parker 10ga. on a #3 frame with 32" fine damascus barrels with great bores, unaltered 2 7/8" chambers choked IM/F, tight ribs with barrels that ring like "church bells", gorgeous DH engraving that is clear and sharp, retaining 60% factory case colors (fading), excellent screws, beautifully figured English grip stock with skeleton butt plate and high modern dimensions. Really a great waterfowler or turkey gun, or for that vintage side by side big bore shoot, this gun is ready to go. The butt stock has been professionally replaced, complete with the original blank stock shield, perfect wood to metal fit, Parker checkering including mullered border, with perfect layout for longevity of use. It could not have been done better. Forend is original to the gun and in excellent refinished condition, no cracks or repairs anywhere on the wood. Serial number 74900 was finished in 1892 (antique, no paper work) as a DH 10ga. hammerless, one of only 633 ever made, only 227 with 32" barrels and likely only a few left in this kind of condition. The hinge pin and locking bolt have been replaced so the gun is like new on hinge and tight on breech face. Bores are bright, .779 bore diameter, choked constrictions of .029/.033, minimum barrel wall thickness of 30 thou right, 33 thou left, no dents, damascus restored to perfection, clear lettering on rib, no pits or dents anywhere. Action is in extraordinary factory original condition with lots of case color and really nice engraving, mechanically perfect. Stock measures 14 3/8" LOP, 2" DAH, 1 3/8" DAC, neutral cast. Gun weighs 8lbs. 12.9 oz. and handles nicely balanced 3/4" forward of the hinge pin. No stopping your swing with this gun! I see a lot of old Parkers, and this gun is an awesome collectible shooter that will continue to increase in value as you break it back in from its like new mechanical condition.

title: For Sale:  Rare WWI German DWM Artillery Luger
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
This is a fine condition and all matching WWI German Artillery Luger manufactured by DWM in 1917. The end of the 1890s and early 1900s saw great international military interest in semiautomatic weapons, particularly handguns. The famous Borchardt design and the Mauser C96 pistol are both examples of this interest at the turn of the century. The German Army expressed interest in a pistol-carbine for artillery use in 1907 and several designs were submitted, including the Borchardt, the C96 by Mauser and others but none were considered satisfactory. The next year, the German Army adopted the new semi-automatic design that was called the Pistole 08 or P08, which is the classic Luger design. The German War Ministry then decided to raise the issue of the pistol-carbine for artillery use again with a view towards creating a design based on the P08 design. Captain Adolf Fischer of the German Army led a team that worked with Deutsche Waffen-und Munitionsfabriken (DWM) to develop a Luger pistol-carbine for German Army artillery units.

The Luger had been around for several years prior to the German Army's adoption of the P08 and, in fact, long-barreled versions had been available in the South American market since 1900. The Imperial German Navy even beat the German Army to the punch with the adoption of their pistol-carbine, the Selbstladepistolen 04 in 1904. Captain Fischer was able to use these designs as a starting point in the development of a pistol-carbine for artillery use. Within a short period of time, Captain Fischer and his team from DWM settled on the standard Luger frame with an 8-inch barrel and an adjustable rear sight calibrated out to 800 meters with a shoulder stock and holster. These first Army qualification trial pistols were made by DWM between 1912 and 1913 and totaled only about 50 pistols. These early weapons had a prototype stock similar to the shoulder stock used on the C96, wherein the pistol itself could be stored. This stock was not retained for the final, accepted version. Ultimately, the design was finalized and the Kaiser himself, Wilhelm II, approved what became the Lange Pistole 08 on June 3, 1913. But because the new weapon was initially developed for Imperial German Artillery units, it has been commonly called the Artillery Luger ever since even though its more technical name is simply Long Pistol 08. 
No Trade

title: For Sale/Trade:  1922 d 'no mint mark' wheat penny
postcontent:
The 1922 "plain" or "no d" can be produced from four different die pairs. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 produce either 
a "weak D" or a "No D". Die Pair #2, which is the most desirable of the four die pairs, always produces a "No D". 

In 1922 only the Denver Mint was responsible for producing Lincoln Cents. Both Mints were busy producing 
millions of Silver Dollars. No nickels, dimes, quarters, or half dollars were produced in 1922. The creation of all 
four die pairs was the result of the Denver Mint running out of usable dies with thousands of cents needed to be 
struck to fill their quota. 

Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 were the result of "mint grease", which is a combination of dirt, metal, and oil, filling the 
area of the mintmark. Mint grease would fill the mintmark gradually, resulting in different levels of "weakness". It 
is believed that the mint grease would fall out, then refill creating a cycle of normal D's, broken D's, weak D's, and 
no D's. When looking at circulated examples of 1922 D's, keep in mind that the mintmark could have simply be 
worn from use. Die Pairs #1, #3 and #4 have "weak reverses" because they were struck with worn reverse dies. 

Die Pair #2 is not believed to be the result of "mint grease". A pair of dies that were creating 1922 D's clashed 
together. The clash resulted in damage to both the obverse and reverse die. The reverse die was badly 
damaged, and replaced with a newer less worn die. The obverse die was reworked by a mint employee who 
erased all traces of the D mintmark while repairing and polishing the die. The result is a worn obverse die with no 
trace of a mintmark and a strong reverse die. 

All 1922 weak D or No D coins fall into one of 7 categories:
1. Die Pair #1 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
2. Die Pair #1 No D (Weak Reverse)
3. Die Pair #2 No D (Strong Reverse) also called 1922 Plain **************************
4. Die Pair #3 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
5. Die Pair #3 No D (Weak Reverse)
6. Die Pair #4 Weak D (Weak Reverse)
7. Die Pair #4 No D (Weak Reverse)
